				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">The Most Ridiculous Comments of the Republican Debate: Readers Weigh In</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Anna North			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-10-30T21:07:08+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">October 30, 2015 5:07 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">October 30, 2015 5:07 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//takingnote.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/10/30/the-most-ridiculous-comments-of-the-republican-debate-readers-weigh-in/" data-title="The Most Ridiculous Comments of the Republican Debate: Readers Weigh In" data-description="Readers called out the candidates, the moderators and The New York Times in our debate survey.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/30/opinion/30northWEB/30northWEB-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/30/opinion/30northWEB/30northWEB-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/30/opinion/30northWEB/30northWEB-blog480.jpg" id="100000004009771" width="480" height="320" alt="Carly Fiorina, Ted Cruz and Chris Christie at the Republican debate on October 28."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Carly Fiorina, Ted Cruz and Chris Christie at the Republican debate on October 28.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Jim Wilson/The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mike Huckabee, Marco Rubio, Carly Fiorina, the moderators â and us. These were some of your answers to <a href="//takingnote.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/10/28/who-made-the-most-ridiculous-comment-in-the-republican-debate/">the question we posed on Wednesday night</a>: âWho made the most ridiculous comment in the Republican debate?â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Over six hundred readers wrote in with their picks. Carly Fiorina got the most votes, followed by Donald Trump and Ted Cruz. Rand Paul and John Kasich got the least. For each candidate, readers submitted a variety of comments that bothered them. A few of the most common choices:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>â</strong><strong>92 percent of the jobs lost during Barack Obamaâs first term belonged to women.â â Carly Fiorina</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âCarly makes false claims with forceful conviction, and some people believe without fact checking,â said Mary, one of the many readers who selected this comment as the most ridiculous of the evening. According to <a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2015/10/28/the-third-republican-debate-annotating-the-transcript/#annotations:8065121">The Washington Post</a>, by the time President Obama was sworn in a second time, âhis jobs record was a net winner, both for men and women. So this claim is utterly wrong.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>âYou want to fix Medicare? Focus on the diseases that are costing us the trillions of dollars. Alzheimerâs, diabetes, heart disease and cancer. Eradicate those and you fix Medicare and youâve fixed America, its economy and youâve made peopleâs lives a heck of a lot better.â â Mike Huckabee</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âAnd a pony for everyone,â added Pat. âNo, a magical, blessed, flying unicorn for everyone.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Â </strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>The Democrats âhave the ultimate super PAC, itâs called the mainstream media.â â Marco Rubio</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Rubio was âjust playing to the audience who thrives on that dated nonsense about a âliberal media,ââ said Mare.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>â</strong><strong>I think the Fed should get out of the business of trying to juice our economy and simply be focused on sound money and monetary stability, ideally tied to gold.</strong><strong>â â Ted Cruz</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWhat year is this, 1950?â asked Jacob B.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>â</strong><strong>You find a Democrat thatâs for cutting taxes â cutting spending ten dollars, Iâll give them a warm kiss.â â Jeb Bush</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIt was stupid, irrelevant, and in bad taste,â said OldDoc. Marrie wrote simply, âCrude.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>âWe can do a wall. Weâre going to have a big, fat beautiful door right in the middle of the wall.Â Weâre going to have people come in, but theyâre coming in legally. And Mexicoâs going to pay for the wall because Mexico âÂ I love the Mexican people; I respect the Mexican leadersÂ âÂ but the leaders are much sharper, smarter and more cunning than our leaders.â â Donald Trump</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWhat are we playing,â asked Stefany. ââGame of Thronesâ??â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A number of readers used the survey not to call out a particular candidate, but to level a more general criticism. A Central Texan took the entire slate to task. âNothing can be more ridiculous than what all have already said: âI am running for the office of President of the United States.â Because none appear particularly capable of doing that job.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A few readers felt the debateâs moderators were more ridiculous than the candidates. âThe most ridiculous things said were the questions from the âmoderators,ââ said P. Kramer. âCNBC should never again be given the responsibility to host such an important national debate.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And several readers expressed frustration with the survey itself. âThe most ridiculous thing was your question, which demonstrates the partisanship of the New York Times,â said Michael Samoszuk. âWhy not also ask, âwhat was the most sensible thing said?ââ And Jeff said he was âcurious whether NYT will solicit similar comments following the Democratic debates.â Answer: We will.</p>
